The extraordinary fact, says Niebuhr, that for seven consecutive years, from 269 to 275, one of the scats in the consulship was always filled by a member of the Fabian house cannot have been the result of accident. It was the price paid by the older tribes to the powerful house in question for their support in an attempt to exclude the lesser houses from the consulship.
